        <name>8.1.2.2 Applying Cramer's rule to system with three equations and three unknowns</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use Cramer's rule to find the y-coordinate of the solution of the system:  &lt;br&gt; \[{@eqns[1]@}\ =\ {@bmat[1,1]@} , \]  \[ {@eqns[2]@}\ =\ {@bmat[2,1]@} , \]  \[ {@eqns[3]@}\ =\ {@bmat[3,1]@} . \] &lt;br&gt; y= [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&amp;nbsp;[[feedback:Result]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;Cramer's rule states that \(y = \frac{\Delta_{y}}{\Delta}\) where \(\Delta\) is the determinant of the matrix and \(\Delta_{y}\) is the determinant of the matrix with the y column replaced by the numbers on the right hand side of
the equations. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Therefore for the system &lt;br&gt; \[{@eqns[1]@}\ =\ {@bmat[1,1]@} , \] \[ {@eqns[2]@}\ =\ {@bmat[2,1]@} , \] \[ {@eqns[3]@}\ =\ {@bmat[3,1]@} , \]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; \[ \Delta = \det{@Amat@}={@D@},\] and&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; \[\Delta_{y} = \det{@Amaty@}={@Dy@},\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;where the notation \(\det A = |A|\) is the determinant of a matrix \(A.\)&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hence, \[y=\frac{\Delta_{y}}{\Delta}=\frac{@Dy@}{@D@} = {@Dy/D@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
